Female (
Fig. 1B
). Eyes small, tempora much longer than diameter of eye. Each elytron with oval, shallow depression (diameter 
0.2 mm
) in apical portion (excitator, 
Fig. 4B
). Close to each depression, in adsutural portion, tuft of longer setae present. Hind wings fully developed. Tergite VIII long (L 
1.05 mm
), with paired apodemes, a few setae and punctures in apical part; sternite VIII shorter (L 
0.68 mm
), with paired apodemes which are connected at base, setae and a few punctures in apical part, basal part weakly emarginated; ovipositor (
Fig. 10A
) long (L 
1.45 mm
); prehensor (
Fig. 10C
) dorsoventrally flattened, oval (L 
1.05 mm
, 

W 
0.60

mm), massive, strongly sclerotized, covered densely with numerous setae, with two triangular sclerotizations in posterior portion, enclosed with much longer and heavier spine-like setae.

Variation. Morphology of parameres variable: the triangular projections may bear two or three denticles which are most visible in lateral view. In the case of specimens from Great Barrier Island the projections are missing and instead spines are present on parameres (
Fig. 9
).
